                            <hr />
            </article>

                                                                                
            
        
    <article class="art-hed mb-4">
        <h3><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/12/duke-palantir-is-welcome-here">Palantir is welcome here</a></h3>
                            <hr />
            </article>

                                                                                
            
        
    <article class="art-hed">
        <h3><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/12/the-tragedy-of-the-toilets-lifestyle">The tragedy of the toilets</a></h3>
                    </article>

                                                                                                </div>
                        

                        <p>Seattle is over 2,400 miles and three time zones away from New York City&mdash;for several of my classmates, Sept. 11, 2001 could not have been closer to home. &nbsp;</p>
<p>I remember my situation completely. I awoke early that morning, 5:45 a.m., to finish my biology homework and listen to my favorite radio show, Jackie and Bender. Nobody else in the house was awake. At 6:10 a.m., Jackie&rsquo;s celebrity gossip was interrupted on the radio.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Holy crap!&rdquo; Bender said. &ldquo;A plane just hit the World Trade Center.&rdquo;</p>
<p>While not the most poignant or respectful exclamation, it certainly captured the shock of the seemingly implausible act. My parents and I sat speechless for several minutes.</p>
<p>When I arrived to my first class, half of my classmates had no idea anything was wrong. It was still early&mdash;even I usually don&rsquo;t hear news that early. &nbsp;</p>
<p>My first-period teacher taught as if nothing was wrong or different. &nbsp;It was somewhat relaxing to continue with everyday life. &nbsp;An assembly was called and the rest of the morning was spent going from class to class, staring at the news in shock. &nbsp;</p>
<p>My friend Lindsey was flying to Boston that morning. &nbsp;Her plane was grounded in a mid-west state. I was far away from the incident that day&mdash;physically and emotionally. I will never be able to understand what others went through. I only felt the great sadness and complete horror that accompanies such an incident.</p>
<p>&mdash; Steve Veres&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><b>Duke University, Durham, N.C.:</b></p>
<p>There was something peculiar about the kids on the East-West bus the morning of Sept. 11, 2001. I was heading back to East Campus after my 9:10 on Science Drive and it seemed as if too many students with New York accents were hunched over their cell phones, speaking in tones far too alert for that time of day.</p>
<p>I still had no clue what had just happened.</p>
<p>Although that quickly changed once I got to my dorm and watched the planes crash into the Twin Towers over and over on CNN, it took me substantially longer to truly internalize what had just happened. Terrorist attacks were things that occurred in remote places like Kenya and Tanzania&mdash;places far far away from here, I thought.</p>
<p>Later that evening, our dorm held a candlelight vigil for the victims of the attacks and it was only then, that the the significance of the tragedy truly began to hit home. Students I knew received calls on their cells phones in the middle of class from family frantically trying to reach them. A girl in my dorm couldn&rsquo;t find her father for days after the attack. One of my neighbor&rsquo;s high school classmates was on the Pennsylvania flight.</p>
<p>&mdash; Liana Wyler</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><b>Bethesda, Md.:</b></p>
<p>Like thousands of students across the country, I first heard of the Sept. 11 attacks between classes. As kids growing up outside Washington, D.C., where the local news is also national and international news, we knew it was something big. We watched the towers fall as we sat in fourth period, unable to do anything but gape at the horror. But it didn&rsquo;t really hit home until they hit the Pentagon.</p>
<p>That was in our backyard; some students had parents who worked there. Even more frightening was the realization that we were just outside the nation&rsquo;s capital, and most of our parents worked downtown&mdash;many in federal government buildings.</p>
<p>Suddenly everyone we knew was crammed into the little newspaper office, using our phone to try and call their parents. There were reports of car bombs downtown, which were thankfully just rumors, and as we left school early that day we could hear the helicopters and airplanes circling above. The federal government was shutting down in panic, and we didn&rsquo;t know what to do.</p>
<p>For the first time, many of us realized that our government, which employed so many kids&rsquo; parents, was truly the object of some people&rsquo;s hatred. That was the scariest thing of all: Our government couldn&rsquo;t protect us from something like this.</p>
<p>&mdash; Karen Hauptman</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><b>New York, N.Y.:</b></p>
<p>We were far enough from any likely targets to really fear for our own lines. There were murmurs on campus that eight planes were still unaccounted for.</p>
<p>We couldn&rsquo;t go home that night. We all packed the homes of our few friends who lived outside Manhattan. We didn&rsquo;t know when we would be able to go back, at that point we didn&rsquo;t know what else might be hit.</p>
<p>That was the kind of day it was. Almost from the beginning I knew this would change everything.</p>
<p>&mdash; Jake Poses</p>
